{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Malaysians of Filipino origin | image = | pop = '''325,089''' | popplace = [[Sabah]], [[Klang Valley|Greater Kuala Lumpur]], [[Johor]] | langs = [[Tausug language|Tausug]], [[Chavacano]], [[Yakan language|Yakan]], [[Iranun language|Iranun]], [[Maranao language|Maranao]], [[Maguindanao language|Maguindanao]], [[Sama-Bajaw languages]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Philippine English|English]], [[Malay language|Malay]] | rels = [[Islam]] and [[Christianity]] | related-c = [[Filipinos]] }}
The '''Filipino Malaysians''' consists of people of full or partial [[Filipino people|Filipino]] descent who were born in or immigrated to [[Malaysia]]. Filipino in Malaysia comprise migrants and residents from the [[Philippines]] and their descendants living in [[Malaysia]]. Because of the short distance between the two nations, many Filipinos mainly from the [[Mindanao]] islands have migrated to the Malaysian state of [[Sabah]] to escape from the [[Moro conflict in the Philippines|war in the Southern Philippines]], [[Poverty in the Philippines|poverty]] and in search for better lives. 325,089 Filipinos live in Malaysia.<ref name="no">{{cite web |url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/news/breakingnews/view/20090206-187868/No-foreign-workers-layoffs-in-Malaysia |title=No foreign workers' layoffs in Malaysia |last=Uy |first=Vernoica |date=6 February 2009 |publisher=Global Enquirer |accessdate=16 February 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209101514/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/news/breakingnews/view/20090206-187868/No-foreign-workers-layoffs-in-Malaysia |archivedate=9 February 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name="ops">{{cite web |url=http://www.ops.gov.ph/namsummit2003/backgrounder.htm |title=Filipino workers in Malaysia |publisher=Office of the Press Secretary |location=Philippines |year=2003 |accessdate=19 November 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423065955/http://www.ops.gov.ph/namsummit2003/backgrounder.htm |archivedate=23 April 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Many of them are illegal residents while there are a smaller number of migrant workers and fewer permanent residents.<ref name="no"/>
== History == Most of the Filipinos especially the [[Bajau people|Bajau]] had lived around the state of Sabah even since before the colonial period, while the [[Tausūg people|Suluk]] had lived on the eastern part of [[Sabah]] from [[Kudat]] to [[Tawau]] as these areas was once under the influence of the [[Sultanate of Sulu]]. Other Filipinos [[Kababayan]] such as [[Hiligaynon people|Ilonggo]], [[Waray people|Waray]], [[Zamboangueño]] (living in Semporna since prior to the creation of Malaysia), [[Tagalog people|Tagalog]], [[Cebuano people|Cebuano]] and [[Bicolanos]] then come to [[North Borneo]] (present-day Sabah) in 1920s and 1930s to work under the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] and various private companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/09/28/kababayan-community-holds-first-gathering-in-sabah/|title=Kababayan community holds first gathering in Sabah|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=28 September 2015|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref> A large number of the Filipinos in Malaysia are [[Moro people|Moros]].
== Labours == In December 2011, an estimated 325,089 Filipinos lived legally in Malaysia.<ref>Department of Foreign Affairs, Philippine Overseas Employment Administration, Commission on Filipinos Overseas</ref> By 2011, 55,828 Filipinos were recorded working on contracts in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldpoliticsreview.com/article.aspx?id=2976|title=Malaysia's Deportation of Filipino Refugees Raises Concerns|last=Hunt|first=Luke|date=27 November 2008|publisher=World Politics Review|accessdate=16 February 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205032711/http://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/article.aspx?id=2976|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A majority of these workers come from the provinces of [[Basilan]], [[Sulu Province|Sulu]], [[Palawan]], [[Tawi-Tawi]], and [[Zamboanga Peninsula (Administrative Region)|Zamboanga Peninsula]].<ref name="ABS"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pia.gov.ph/?m=12&fi=p070516.htm&date=05/16/2007|title="Home is where greener pasture is," DSWD tells illegal Filipinos in Sabah|date=16 May 2007|publisher=Philippine Information Agency|accessdate=16 February 2009}}</ref> There are at least 25 Filipino community organisations in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philembassykl.org.my/filcom.htm|title=Useful Information for Filipinos in Malaysia |date=10 July 2008|publisher=phil.embassy.kl|accessdate=16 February 2009}}</ref>
==Illegal immigration and crime issues== {{See also|Refugees of the Philippines|Illegal immigrants in Malaysia|Cross border attacks in Sabah}} The majority of undocumented Filipinos live in the Malaysian state of Sabah,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dole.gov.ph/news/details.asp?id=N000000313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303185538/http://www.dole.gov.ph/news/details.asp?id=N000000313|dead-url=yes|archive-date=3 March 2016|title=Undocumented Filipino migrants in Malaysia to be assisted|date=1 February 2005|publisher=[[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|DOLE]] News|accessdate=16 February 2009}}</ref> with most of them coming from the Mindanao islands. They are frequently targeted by the Malaysian immigration for repatriation. In 2002, the first major crackdown on [[illegal immigration]] occurred, with around 64,000 Filipinos being repatriated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philippines.hvu.nl/facts7.htm|title=Filipino's working abroad |year=2002|publisher=Hogeschool Utecht|accessdate=17 February 2009}}</ref> Around 4,000 to 6,000 Filipinos are deported each year for immigration offences,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trafficking.org.ph/v5/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1014&Itemid=56|title=330 Filipinos home after being deported from Sabah |last=Jacinto|first=Al|date=17 October 2005|publisher=Manila Times|accessdate=16 February 2009}}</ref> and the [[Government of the Philippines|Philippines government]] says that there is a large number of Filipinos detained in various immigration centres of Malaysia awaiting [[deportation]]. Some of these reportedly include children younger than 19 years old.<ref name="ABS">{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/pinoy-migration/02/16/09/300-illegal-pinoys-deported-malaysia|title=300 illegal Pinoys deported from Malaysia|date=17 February 2009|publisher=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=17 February 2009}}</ref> Many of them are deported because of overstaying their visas, or being involved in crime. Nearly 72% of the prison population in Sabah are Filipinos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2015/03/19/sabah-inmates-58p-foreign/|title=Foreigners make up 58% of Sabah prison inmates|work=Bernama|publisher=The Star|date=19 March 2015|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>
Since the attack by [[Jamalul Kiram III|Kiram's]] in 2013, more Filipinos in the state facing an increase on [[discrimination]] and became the possible target for retaliation especially from the local Borneo tribes due to the killing of Malaysian police who mainly comprising the indigenous Borneo races.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/23164-pinoys-in-sabah-fear-retaliation |title=Pinoys in Sabah fear retaliation |author=Charlie Saceda |publisher=Rappler |date=6 March 2013 |accessdate=7 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024030440/http://www.rappler.com/nation/23164-pinoys-in-sabah-fear-retaliation |archivedate=24 October 2015 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>
==Notable people== <small>Almost all figures in the list of the notable people Filipino descent in Malaysia are of mixed descent, particularly with the natives of Sabah. Mixed-marriage is a pattern which is shared with most of Filipino descent in Malaysia (excluding to the recently arrived migrants), after settling in the Malaysian soil after generations, assimilation process and the common Islamic background.</small> * Arshad Zamir - Actor and a contestant on [[MasterChef Malaysia]] * Yazmin Aziz - Singer and girlfriend of Michael Pacquiao (son of Manny Pacquiao) * Bella Dally - Actress * [[Wawa Zainal Abidin|Wawa Zainal]] - Actress * [[Hans Isaac]] - Actor * Iqbal Mazlan - Actor * Julfekar - Composer * Melinda Roos - Writer * Maria Farida - Actress
