'''Gounder''' is a title used by various communities originating in the [[Indian state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-05-21/chennai/28179309_1_poll-observers-assembly-polls-poll-eve | work=The Times Of India | title=Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties}}</ref> It may refer to [[Kongu Vellalar]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dinamalar.com/News_Detail.asp?id=209220&Print=1 |title=கொங்கு நாடு யாருக்கு: வரிசை கட்டும் பிரச்னைகள் - கவுண்டர் சமுதாயத்தை ...கடந்த கோபமாக கொங்கு வேளாளக் கவுண்டர்கள் , Kongu Vellala Gounders are angry that Gounder community is being targeted by registering cases against them |language=Tamil |accessdate=December 15, 2011 |work=[[Dinamalar]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/newly-elected-ministers-be-sworn-today-234 Newly elected ministers to be sworn in today | Deccan Chronicle<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106145349/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/newly-elected-ministers-be-sworn-today-234 |date=2011-11-06 }}</ref> [[Vanniyar]]s,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v7EWAAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=palli+gounder|title=Agriculture and social structure in Tamil Nadu ; past origins, present transformations, and future prospects|author=Joan P. Mencher}}</ref> [[Vettuvar]]s,<ref name="Madhavan" /> [[Kuruba|Gollas]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Equal in the Eyes of God: a South Indian Devotional Group in its Hierarchical Setting |first1=Geoffrey |last1=Burkhart |page=8 |title=Contributions to Asian studies |volume=5 |publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |location=Leiden |year=1974 |isbn=978-90-04-03967-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OREVAAAAIAAJ |accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> and [[Urali Gounder|Uralis]].<ref> |language=Tamil |accessdate=December 15, 2011 |work=[[Dinamani]]}}</ref>{{Request quotation|date=January 2016}}
==Etymology== There are number of derivations for the title. One theory derives the name Gounder from [[Tamil language|Tamil]] word ''Kaamindan'', meaning noble protector of the country. It was later modified as ''Kavundan'' or Gounder.<ref name="Madhavan">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fline/fl2516/stories/20080815251611400.htm|title=Steeped in history|last=Madhvan|first=Karthik|date=2 August 2008|work=Frontline|publisher=The Hindu Group|accessdate=22 January 2011|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>
==History== During the [[British Raj]] era, some Gounders migrated to Malaya rubber plantations to work in the [[kangani system]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Raj Sekhar |last=Basu |title=Nandanar's Children: The Paraiyans' Tryst with Destiny, Tamil Nadu 1850 - 1956 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4NeGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA137 |year=2011 |publisher=SAGE |isbn=978-81-321-0679-1 |page=137}}</ref>
